statement:
Let A be a $2\times{2}$ matrix which transforms

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix} \quad \text{to} \quad \begin{bmatrix}
2\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and transforms

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix} \quad \text{to} \quad \begin{bmatrix}
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

What are the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of A?

sols:
From the hint we recall that an eigenvalue, eigenvector pair satisfies,

\begin{align*}A\mathbf{x}=\lambda\mathbf{x}.\end{align*}

We have in our problem that {[}1,1{]} transforms to {[}2,2{]}, which in
matrix form is,

\begin{align*}A
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
2
\end{bmatrix}
=
2
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Therefore we see that {[}1,1{]} is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue
2. For the other case we have that {[}1,-1{]} gets transformed to
{[}0,0{]}. Therefore,

\begin{align*}A
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
=
0
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and so we see that {[}1,-1{]} is also an eigenvector with eigenvalue 0.
Recall that an $n\times{n}$ matrix has at most n eigenvalues. Therefore
since in this case, n=2, we have found all the eigenvalues of the
system. We conclude that A has eigenvalues and eigenvectors,

\begin{align*}
\lambda_1&=2,\quad{}\mathbf{x}_1=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\\
\lambda_2&=0,\quad{}\mathbf{x}_2=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
-1
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}
